                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="false">
                                <p>Modern binding. Modern undecorated parchment over boards. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>, stamped: <quote>Cod. Holm. A 223</quote>. Current binding from 1977.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="390" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="290" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="100" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                            </binding>
                            <binding contemporary="true">
                                <p>Original/medieval binding. Brown leather over wooden boards. Upper part of <locus from="Original_RCO" to="Original_RCO" scheme="other"/>, traces of title in dark ink: <quote>de civitate d</quote>.</p>
                                <decoNote type="tooling">
                                    <p>Concentric sets of panels, some of which are filled with complex knotwork ornaments. These ornaments are decorated with rope patterns. The centre panel contains a geometrical star-like pattern. Many of the tooled elements were gilded. Traces of the gold remain. The bookbinder notes that if the preserved binding is contemporary with the text, then it is one of the oldest preserved examples of gold stamped decoration on leather binding. Hobson states that the star-pattern <quote>is the only known western gilt binding derived from the Mamluk geometrical style</quote> (cf <bibl>
                                            <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107266">Hobson (1989)</title>
                                            <citedRange from="26" to="26" unit="page"/>
                                        </bibl>).</p>
                                </decoNote>
                                <condition>The original binding was renovated in 1850 and removed in 1977. It is now stored separately from the manuscript. The leather is very worn, faded, and riddled with wormholes. <locus from="Original_LCO" to="Original_LCO" scheme="other"/>, remains of four clasps with scallop-shaped brass rivets and red cloth inserts. <locus from="Original_RCO" to="Original_RCO" scheme="other"/>, remains of nails and labels. The images <locus from="Archive_photo_1" to="Archive_photo_1" scheme="other"/> to <locus from="Bookbinder_report_2" to="Bookbinder_report_2" scheme="other"/> illustrate the different steps and results of the rebinding process.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100036">Italy</placeName>
                                </origPlace>, <origDate when="1433">1433</origDate>
                            </p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p> According to <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107266">Hobson (1989)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="25" to="25" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>, <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102569">Albinia De la Mare</persName> suggests that the manuscript might be Venetian based on the decoration, but in a letter to librarian <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102570"> Harry Järv</persName> de la Mare guessses at a Florentine provenance (letter from 3 May 1967). On <locus from="29" to="29" scheme="pages"/> there is a coat of arms which according to <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/101301">Hedlund (1980)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="20" to="20" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl> belongs to the Dusmet family. However, this family does not seem to be established in Italy until the 18th century. On <locus from="710" to="710" scheme="pages"/> there are some faint traces of text, now completely illegible. In <date when="1935"/> these notes were photographed and deciphered by a <quote>doc. Bäckström</quote>. His reading was: <quote>Hunc Augustinum De ciuitate dei donauit reverendissimus <sic>domnus</sic> Baptista de Lignane patauiensis episcopus concondiensis congregationi regularium canonicorum lateranensium ut inprimis sit ad usum studiosorum anno ?Sancti Johannis pro eius anima deuote precare memineritis?.</quote> (The final part of the transcritpion is incomplete.)</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p> Baptista de Legnano, also known as Joannes Baptista Legname was bishop of Concordia 1443-55.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>In Sweden the manuscript is first attested in Jaches's catalogue of 1695 and that of 1698: <quote>nr 25</quote>, U 118; <quote>193</quote>, U 122. The note on <locus from="Original_LCI" to="Original_LCI" scheme="other"/>
                                <quote>K.B. 1734 n. 19 in folio Theol</quote> refers to the catalogue of 1734 (U 125e).</p>
                        </provenance>
                    </history>
